properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow on the way beginning tonight into Tuesday morning. A low pressure system will emerge from Texas and track towards the Great Lakes today. This system will bring an area of snow with it, arriving tonight east of Georgian Bay. The snow will arrive Tuesday morning near and east of the National Capital region. Total snowfall amounts near 10 cm appear likely in most areas, with locally higher amounts up to 15 cm possible in the Ottawa Valley by the time the snow moves out of the area Tuesday evening. There is some uncertainty as to the exact track of the low, which will affect how much snow falls at a particular location. Poor winter driving conditions from accumulating snow and low visibility in areas of heavier snow are expected beginning tonight. Motorists should be prepared to adjust their travel plans accordingly. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-02-18T08:05:32-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowstorm beginning this evening. A low pressure system from Texas will bring an area of snow with it, arriving early this evening in the Sault Ste. Marie area. The snow will then quickly spread to remaining regions north of Lake Huron and Georgian Bay by midnight. Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 20 cm are expected by mid morning on Tuesday. The snow will taper to a few flurries Tuesday morning as the low moves across Lake Huron and Georgian Bay into Quebec. Driving conditions will quickly deteriorate after the snow arrives this evening. Motorists should allow extra time to reach their destination. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for overnight and Tuesday. A band of snow will move over Eastern Ontario starting after 2 AM. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, rain, and strong southerly winds expected on Wednesday. Total snowfall amounts (all of Newfoundland): 5 to 10 cm with some pockets of up to 15 cm possible. Total rainfall amounts (southern and eastern Newfoundland only): 15 to 25 mm, possibly higher over the Burin and southern Avalon Peninsulas. Maximum wind gusts: southerly generally between 60 to 80 km/h except 100 to 120 km/h across parts of western, southern, and eastern Newfoundland. Locations of only snow (no changeover to rain): western and northern Newfoundland. Locations of snow changing to rain: southern, eastern, and most of central Newfoundland. Time span: early Wednesday morning until Wednesday evening. Remarks: Snow will develop over southwestern Newfoundland before dawn on Wednesday and spread across the Island Wednesday morning. Strong southerly winds will accompany the snow causing a few hours of poor visibilities in snow and blowing snow over all areas on Wednesday morning. The snow will change to rain over southern, eastern, and most of central Newfoundland. The precipitation will taper off over western Newfoundland Wednesday afternoon and over eastern Newfoundland Wednesday evening. The public should prepare for poor travel conditions on Wednesday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
